{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"877a51c4-8559-458d-90ac-dacb8b6b0382","content":"The project directory doesn't exist yet. No worries — here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Makes it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n\n  <!-- Must be Exe for stdio transport -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n</PropertyGroup>\n\n<!-- Include a README in the package -->\n<ItemGroup>\n  <None Include=\"README.md\" Pack=\"true\" PackagePath=\"/\" />\n</ItemGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — this is the critical property that makes it installable via `dotnet tool install`.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will type (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType=Exe`** — required since it runs as a standalone process over stdio.\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs the MCP server\n```\n\nWould you like me to scaffold the project with these settings?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6a25419b-d2c0-4435-910c-a5e9daf24a87","outputTokens":528,"requestId":"5C43:1CB4B6:1C2B967:1F4DE80:69FA93BA"},"id":"c3c2ba77-495b-4182-a367-d91cd50fdbb8","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:05:11.374Z","parentId":